body:
There is  an assumption in Dedup that an NLA can only target one thing: an `op` or a `port`.  This is because each op and port is normally assigned a unique symbol which is referenced  by the NLA, making it impossible for the NLA to target more than one thing. 

For memories, they do not have port symbols, so the NLA used for ports actually targets the op itself.  This means that it's possible that a memory annotation and a memory port annotation share the same NLA.  This causes the Dedup pass to only update the last seen use of an NLA when adding more context to a non-local annotation.
 
To solve this we need to either
a) start attaching port symbols to memories, or 
b) start tracking a vector of targets for every NLA, changing the target map from `DenseMap<Attribute, AnnoTarget>` to `DenseMap<Attribute, std::vector<AnnoTarget>`, or
c)  special case all the logic to handle memory ops.

Fixing this is not extremely critical for two reasons:
1. (edit: dedup has to run after reset inference and that puts it after LowerCHIRRTL :( )  The dedup pass runs before LowerCHIRRTL, so it will not actually see any `MemOps` coming from Chisel.  There is no problem with CHIRRTL memory port ops.
2. The annotation attaching logic does not reuse NLAs (yet), it creates a new NLA for each annotation.

Example:
```mlir
// ./bin/circt-opt --firrtl-dedup test.mlir
firrtl.nla @portcontext_nla [#hw.innerNameRef<@PortContext0::@leaf>, #hw.innerNameRef<@PortContextLeaf::@mem>]
firrtl.module @PortContextLeaf() {
  %mem_r = firrtl.mem Undefined  {depth = 16 : i64, name = "mem", portNames = ["r"], readLatency = 0 : i32, writeLatency = 1 : i32,
    annotations     =  [{circt.nonlocal = @portcontext_nla, class = "mem"}],
    portAnnotations = [[{circt.nonlocal = @portcontext_nla, class = "port"}]]}
  : !firrtl.bundle<addr: uint<4>, en: uint<1>, clk: clock, data flip: uint<8>>
}
firrtl.module @PortContext0() {
  firrtl.instance leaf sym @leaf {annotations = [{circt.nonlocal = @portcontext_nla, class = "circt.nonlocal"}]} @PortContextLeaf()
}
firrtl.module @PortContext1() {
  firrtl.instance lead sym @leaf {annotations = [{circt.nonlocal = @portcontext_nla, class = "circt.nonlocal"}]} @PortContextLeaf()
}
firrtl.module @PortContext() {
  firrtl.instance portcontext0 @PortContext0()
  firrtl.instance portcontext1 @PortContext1()
}
```
Produces:
```mlir
firrtl.module @PortContextLeaf() {
  %mem_r = firrtl.mem Undefined  {annotations = [{circt.nonlocal = @portcontext_nla, class = "mem"}], depth = 16 : i64, name = "mem", portAnnotations = [[{circt.nonlocal = @nla_17, class = "port"}]], portNames = ["r"], readLatency = 0 : i32, writeLatency = 1 : i32} : !firrtl.bundle<addr: uint<4>, en: uint<1>, clk: clock, data flip: uint<8>>
}
firrtl.nla @nla_17 [#hw.innerNameRef<@PortContext::@portcontext0>, #hw.innerNameRef<@PortContext0::@leaf>, #hw.innerNameRef<@PortContextLeaf::@mem>]
firrtl.module @PortContext0() {
  firrtl.instance leaf sym @leaf  {annotations = [{circt.nonlocal = @nla_17, class = "circt.nonlocal"}]} @PortContextLeaf()
}
firrtl.module @PortContext() {
  firrtl.instance portcontext0 sym @portcontext0  {annotations = [{circt.nonlocal = @nla_17, class = "circt.nonlocal"}]} @PortContext0()
  firrtl.instance portcontext1  @PortContext0()
}
```

The issue is that the first annotation still is referencing `circt.nonlocal = @portcontext_nla` which no longer exists.
